honkhonk 2025-09-22 10:12 p.m.
# ORDER
MOTION TO RECONSIDER DENIED

The spirit of the legislation does not allow for assisted deaths to be abused to allow consensual fights. And, even if there were intent of actual euthanization, the aforementioned events cannot qualify as a legal euthanization because not all prongs required in 5 MSC 1 8202 were met. There is no explicit stated consent beforehand. The target was not suffering from debilitated physical condition that prevented them from playing the game. The act was not executed with a legal FIREARM. It was not conducted a reasonable distance away from bystanders. The act was not carried out swiftly and painlessly by a bullet to the head. What I saw today was savagery. There was no intent to legally euthanize.

On the matter of the distinction of live fires, there is a prior casem SADOIMPACTO v. CLARK COUNTY SHERIFFS OFFICE; MAYFLOWER NATIONAL GUARD; STATE OF MAYFLOWER, that enjoined any sort of live fires taking place anywhere within the town of Mersea.

bob.gov 2025-10-01 04:17 p.m.
Verbal motion to reconsider order on denial of motion to reconsider:

By the Respondents own argument, habeas corpus should be granted, it is well established that habeas relief is appropriate where an arrest lacks probable cause. See Gerstein v. Pugh, 420 U.S. 103, 11112 (1975) ([T]he Fourth Amendment requires a timely judicial determination of probable cause as a prerequisite to extended restraint of liberty following arrest.).

Under the entrapment doctrine, the government may not induce criminal conduct and then punish the individual for actions the government itself instigated. Sorrells v. United States, 287 U.S. 435, 441 (1932); Sherman v. United States, 356 U.S. 369, 372 (1958). While entrapment is ordinarily raised as an affirmative defense, courts have also recognized that officers cannot lawfully manufacture probable cause by contriving the criminal act themselves. See United States v. Russell, 411 U.S. 423, 435 (1973) (recognizing the due process limitations on government creation of crime).

the officer created the very circumstance that gave rise to the arrest: by intentionally walking into a bat, he manufactured the appearance of an assault. Such conduct cannot supply probable cause. As the Supreme Court held in Illinois v. Gates, 462 U.S. 213, 238 (1983), probable cause must rest on a fair probability that a crime has been committed, not on facts fabricated or induced by the state itself.

Probable cause may have existed had the arrest been based solely on the petitioners actual striking of MPD officers. However, once the MPD officers themselves informed the agent that they had consented to being struck thereby negating the unlawful character of the act any arguable probable cause evaporated. Consent, as recognized in assault law, eliminates the criminality of the conduct. See People v. Samuels, 250 Cal. App. 2d 501, 513 (1967) (consent can be a defense where it negates an element of the crime).
honkhonk 2025-10-04 04:38 a.m.
Denied
cc: @bob.gov @k
honkhonk 2025-10-04 05:08 a.m.
Your citation of People v. Samuels is very misleading.
honkhonk 2025-10-04 05:20 a.m.
In that case, the court rejected the defendants argument that the victims consent to being beaten or injured for a sadomasochistic film excused the conduct. The reasoning behind this was that a person cannot legally consent to an assault that causes or threatens serious bodily injury, because such acts are contrary to public policy. It also included that "even if the alleged victims had consented, such consent would be immaterial." The case did acknowledge a general rule that consent can negate criminality in lesser cases, when the contact is minor or socially acceptable [sports, medical settings, etc]. In People v. Samuels, just like this case here, such rule does not apply because the conduct is too severe.
honkhonk 2025-10-04 05:26 a.m.
And, this notion that the officer manufactured the circumstances by walking into the bat is also very misleading.
honkhonk 2025-10-04 05:44 a.m.
You were swinging a dangerous weapon in a public setting. When the respondent lawfully moved to intervene, you might have not intended to hit the respondent, but you acted with reckless disregard for whether your blows would hit another person. This suffices for assault. A person who swings a weapon during a violent encounter assumes the risk of striking anyone lawfully attempting to stop them, including police officers. See, e.g., People v. Williams, 26 Cal. 4th 779 (2001): assault here is defined by intent to commit an act likely to result in force, not by intent to cause specific injury. This definition falls in line with our state assault laws.

Police officers, by virtue of their office and oath, have a legal and professional duty to take reasonable action when they witness a crime, especially when it involves violence or a threat to life. The respondent took the correct action legally expected of him when he walked towards you while you were swinging at someone else. It is not correct to say he fabricated the grounds for the assault when it already existed while you were swinging.(edited)
